  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions spans several decades and involves international cooperation to combat financial crimes. Here's an overview:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Emerged as a legal concept in the 1970s\n- Initially focused on criminal proceeds from drug trafficking\n- United States passed the Bank Secrecy Act in 1970, requiring financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n\n2. Key Milestones:\n- 1980s: Increased international attention to money laundering\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established to develop global anti-money laundering standards\n- 1990: United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances\n\n3. Major Legislative Developments:\n- US Money Laundering Control Act (1986)\n- US Anti-Drug Abuse Act (1988)\n- US Annunzio-Wylie Anti-Money Laundering Act (1992)\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) significantly expanded money laundering regulations\n\n4. International Frameworks:\n- UN Conventions\n- FATF Recommendations\n- European Union Directives\n- Proliferation of international cooperation mechanisms\n\nThe legal framework continues to evolve in response to emerging financial technologies and criminal strategies.",
